00:41:50.210 --> 00:41:52.490
Therefore, no time
for fear then.

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:56.450
MALE SPEAKER: Speaking about
no good deeds going unpunished,

00:41:56.450 --> 00:41:59.800
I have a question for
you, my friend, Walter.

00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:02.140
So the question is,
what's a nice guy

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:03.676
doing in a place like this?

00:42:03.676 --> 00:42:05.300
I'd like to know
about your involvement

00:42:05.300 --> 00:42:07.020
in this organization.

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:09.280
Specifically, I'm
interested to know--

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:11.770
I know that your
organization is trying

00:42:11.770 --> 00:42:14.620
to change the
economics of the world,

00:42:14.620 --> 00:42:18.060
and I'd like to hear your
views on that as well.

00:42:18.060 --> 00:42:22.900
DR. WALTER LINK: As you can
notice, Ari is very convincing,

00:42:22.900 --> 00:42:26.270
so he just basically
recruited me.

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:31.190
I was organizing at the
conference at Omega Institute

00:42:31.190 --> 00:42:33.720
that I was on the
board on in New York,

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:39.460
and Ari came and he walked
straight to me and he said,

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:42.400
I need you to come
to Sri Lanka and help

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:45.070
us bring this organization
in the 21st century

00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:47.760
because we have a
very good thing going,

00:42:47.760 --> 00:42:53.020
but we need to understand
how to take the next step,

00:42:53.020 --> 00:42:56.700
both in terms of the economic
and the political and social

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:58.400
development environment
and so forth.

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:02.300
And I think what was
relevant in this,

00:43:02.300 --> 00:43:06.170
we are-- I think all three
of us-- we are interested not

00:43:06.170 --> 00:43:10.780
only to work on a project, even
though a project is important,

00:43:10.780 --> 00:43:14.290
but we want to create movements.

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:18.930
And he had read
a book that I had

00:43:18.930 --> 00:43:23.850
edited about global leadership,
which was a movement that we

00:43:23.850 --> 00:43:27.780
are continuing to try to bring
into the world which really

00:43:27.780 --> 00:43:31.820
looks at all the sectors
of society and sees

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:34.320
how can we really
bring about, you

00:43:34.320 --> 00:43:39.140
could say a sustainable adjust,
but also very functional

00:43:39.140 --> 00:43:42.020
innovation there.

00:43:42.020 --> 00:43:46.080
And his organization works
in all sectors of society.

00:43:46.080 --> 00:43:48.290
So it really
requires a rethinking

00:43:48.290 --> 00:43:51.160
of all these different
things, and I myself

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:53.760
came from running a
big, traditional company

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:58.070
and then moved on to
transforming business

00:43:58.070 --> 00:44:02.560
by bringing together many people
who owned and ran companies

00:44:02.560 --> 00:44:06.300
to show there is really a
different way and it works.

00:44:06.300 --> 00:44:08.930
It's not some kind of ideal.

00:44:08.930 --> 00:44:11.040
Because I think
that's really what

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:13.660
makes a real, concrete movement.

00:44:13.660 --> 00:44:19.460
It's not just to have an
aspiration that is inspiring

00:44:19.460 --> 00:44:21.650
but then people
look at their life

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:25.050
and the stretch seems
too big and there's

00:44:25.050 --> 00:44:29.760
no guidance about how to move
from where they are to actually

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:34.350
implementing the changes
that are necessary to reach

00:44:34.350 --> 00:44:36.940
that inspirational place.

00:44:36.940 --> 00:44:42.730
And so that's where we
started to deep dialogue

00:44:42.730 --> 00:44:45.560
and deep collaborations
in bringing

00:44:45.560 --> 00:44:48.490
about these movements, not
only in Sri Lanka but also

00:44:48.490 --> 00:44:50.346
internationally.

00:44:50.346 --> 00:44:54.990
MALE SPEAKER: Dr. Ari, I
have a question for you.

00:44:54.990 --> 00:44:57.270
There are so many things
about you that inspire me

00:44:57.270 --> 00:45:00.280
and one of those many things
is that what you do actually

00:45:00.280 --> 00:45:01.810
works.

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:04.339
And so I compare what you
do to international aid,

00:45:04.339 --> 00:45:06.130
when rich countries
keep the poor countries

00:45:06.130 --> 00:45:08.104
and the money just
disappear to corruption,

00:45:08.104 --> 00:45:09.020
but you don't do that.

00:45:09.020 --> 00:45:09.780
You start doing nothing.

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:11.560
You're just a
schoolteacher, and what

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:15.320
you did was inspire people to
give the gift of labor and love

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:18.420
to each other and in
doing so it created

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:22.590
the whole massive movement,
like 15,000 bridges, millions

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:25.020
of dollars, schools, and
so forth, have been built.

00:45:25.020 --> 00:45:29.830
And so my question
for you is, first,

00:45:29.830 --> 00:45:33.470
how, what can people learn
from this thing that you did,

00:45:33.470 --> 00:45:37.150
that inspired people to be
able to give to each other?

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:40.910
And also, I'm interested to
know about grassroot democracy,

00:45:40.910 --> 00:45:42.840
and I know you've done
some thinking somewhat

00:45:42.840 --> 00:45:45.620
in that field, and I want to
know what's the current state

00:45:45.620 --> 00:45:47.634
and what can we learn
from that as well?

00:45:47.634 --> 00:45:50.490
DR. A.T. ARIYARATNE:
You may remember

00:45:50.490 --> 00:45:54.480
I started by talking about
individual personality

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:56.330
reasoning.

00:45:56.330 --> 00:45:58.870
Next comes family
then the community

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:01.930
then groups and
nations and the world.

00:46:01.930 --> 00:46:07.330
So awakening is something that
could be implemented, starting

00:46:07.330 --> 00:46:10.590
from the individual
to the world level.

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:14.340
But, unfortunately, most of
the modern economic, social,

00:46:14.340 --> 00:46:21.430
and political theories are
based on not naturalistical kind

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:26.640
of approach, not for
the well being of all.

00:46:26.640 --> 00:46:29.190
Well being of the majority.

00:46:29.190 --> 00:46:31.880
That Mahatma Gandhi
coined word sarvodaya,

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:36.450
which we adopted from India.

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:40.300
Because our language
also rooted in Sanskrit,

00:46:40.300 --> 00:46:44.480
So this word was
similar to our language.

00:46:44.480 --> 00:46:49.980
So we adopted the word
sarvodaya from Mahatma Gandhi.

00:46:49.980 --> 00:46:56.920
So this concept
of working for all

00:46:56.920 --> 00:47:00.910
is something that Buddhists try
to always have. [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:04.260 --> 00:47:07.390
May all beings be
well and happy.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:11.940
Now if I-- if a mosquito
lights on my hand,

00:47:11.940 --> 00:47:16.510
if I kill the mosquito, my
mother will turn to me and say,

00:47:16.510 --> 00:47:19.520
why did you kill that mosquito?

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:22.820
That mosquito also
has a right to live.

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:25.080
Where else can
this mosquito live?

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:28.020
You should have
chased him out or not

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:32.950
allowed mosquitoes to breed.

00:47:32.950 --> 00:47:40.755
So respect for life is
the eye of our culture.

00:47:40.755 --> 00:47:44.200
That life is the art the
heart of every living being.

00:47:44.200 --> 00:47:49.450
So we had to think of
development models, which

00:47:49.450 --> 00:47:53.540
take this kind of basic
truths into consideration.

00:47:53.540 --> 00:47:57.070
So truth, nonviolence,
and self-reliance,

00:47:57.070 --> 00:48:01.590
were the three principles
on which we started.

00:48:01.590 --> 00:48:05.910
We told our communities,
you are poor.

00:48:05.910 --> 00:48:08.580
Governments if they
have no money therefore

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:11.600
they can't give you a
water service scheme.

00:48:11.600 --> 00:48:15.470
Wells or irrigation
tanks or anything.

00:48:15.470 --> 00:48:18.060
Why do we did?

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:24.240
In the modern economies you
talk of land, labor, capital,

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:26.275
and entrepreneurship,
like what you

00:48:26.275 --> 00:48:28.470
were taught in the universities.

00:48:28.470 --> 00:48:33.250
But in our ancient culture
it's not land, it's nature.

00:48:33.250 --> 00:48:38.010
It's not labor, it's
human personality.

00:48:38.010 --> 00:48:43.940
It's not money, it's not
capital, it's social wealth.

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:48.150
It's not entrepreneurship
only, it is science and wisdom.

00:48:48.150 --> 00:48:49.760
Ancient culture.

00:48:49.760 --> 00:48:53.220
Let us bring these five
factors of progress

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:55.840
together and see what happens.

00:48:55.840 --> 00:49:00.220
Thousands of people to join to
cut the road to the village.

00:49:00.220 --> 00:49:01.850
Dig wells.

00:49:01.850 --> 00:49:03.660
From nature itself
collect material

00:49:03.660 --> 00:49:09.140
and put up houses, not big,
concrete, modern houses,

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:13.290
but livable houses with plenty
of yard and sunlight and all

00:49:13.290 --> 00:49:14.540
that.

00:49:14.540 --> 00:49:19.950
So that kind of
creativity, they never

00:49:19.950 --> 00:49:24.510
thought of after they
became independent in 1948

00:49:24.510 --> 00:49:28.550
they thought of imitating
of the western world who

00:49:28.550 --> 00:49:32.230
had a lot of money from
exploitation, from conquests.

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:35.140
We didn't have that
kind of capital.

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:39.360
So we had to have
our own process

00:49:39.360 --> 00:49:43.270
and we call it an
awakening process,

00:49:43.270 --> 00:49:49.320
and then of course the problem
we have is all these things

00:49:49.320 --> 00:49:57.700
are imitated by governments and
others with limited objectives.

00:49:57.700 --> 00:50:00.740
Political or
profitable objectives.

00:50:00.740 --> 00:50:04.820
But not for the [INAUDIBLE]
being of humanity

00:50:04.820 --> 00:50:12.140
but now I think there are
many institutions from around

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:14.140
the world come and
spend time with us

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:19.710
from universities, scholars,
World Bank, and IMF

00:50:19.710 --> 00:50:24.190
and all these organizations
come, and I am really careful.

00:50:24.190 --> 00:50:26.430
We have several thousand
working in the moment.

00:50:26.430 --> 00:50:28.970
full time and many
more [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:28.970 --> 00:50:31.425
I told them to be
very, very careful

00:50:31.425 --> 00:50:33.001
of experts and consultants.

00:50:36.090 --> 00:50:37.670
You know that joke
about consultants?

00:50:37.670 --> 00:50:42.330
A consultant went to the village
and asked a village woman,

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:44.780
your hen lays eggs every day?

00:50:47.310 --> 00:50:48.030
Any problem?

00:50:48.030 --> 00:50:50.560
No problem.

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:52.660
Then this expert was
very disappointed

00:50:52.660 --> 00:50:56.750
because there was nobody
to get advice from him.

00:50:56.750 --> 00:50:59.425
When he was getting
into the car,

00:50:59.425 --> 00:51:03.250
the woman ran to the expert
and said, yes, sir, I

00:51:03.250 --> 00:51:05.250
have a problem.

00:51:05.250 --> 00:51:08.310
Can you tell me
how to distinguish

00:51:08.310 --> 00:51:10.465
between a male chick
and a female chick.

00:51:13.260 --> 00:51:15.970
He said, you have to
ask the chicken expert.

00:51:15.970 --> 00:51:19.370
I am only some other expert.

00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:21.361
So experts come and go.

00:51:21.361 --> 00:51:22.860
I have been an
expert myself for one

00:51:22.860 --> 00:51:28.260
and a half am months in Uganda.

00:51:28.260 --> 00:51:32.370
I was paid so much
I felt sick of it.

00:51:32.370 --> 00:51:37.580
I got a another one recommended
to do my job and I came home.

00:51:37.580 --> 00:51:39.380
I didn't know what to
with all that money.

00:51:42.040 --> 00:51:44.940
[INAUDIBLE] and there's
a nice meditation center.

00:51:44.940 --> 00:51:47.755
All of you can
come and meditate.

00:51:47.755 --> 00:51:51.590
MALE SPEAKER: I have one last
question for both of you, which

00:51:51.590 --> 00:51:55.020
is how are you going to turn
this into a global movement

00:51:55.020 --> 00:51:56.710
and how do we help you do that?

00:52:00.662 --> 00:52:07.310
DR. A.T. ARIYARATNE: I think
this world needs three things

00:52:07.310 --> 00:52:09.465
to happen.

00:52:09.465 --> 00:52:14.050
If we are to eliminate
conflict as well as hunger

00:52:14.050 --> 00:52:19.610
and other causes for
this present situation,

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:32.360
one is, democratize the
economic and social life

00:52:32.360 --> 00:52:38.090
by decentralized planning
and organization, what

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:39.235
we call ground surround.

00:52:41.780 --> 00:52:44.020
Have governments of communities.

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:50.436
Imagine the planet with
communities of 100 families,

00:52:50.436 --> 00:52:52.980
maybe 200 families, maybe
a little less, maybe

00:52:52.980 --> 00:53:00.070
a little more, having maximum
possible freedom to decide

00:53:00.070 --> 00:53:03.250
what they want to do with least
interference from the top.

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:04.800
That is one.

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:11.640
Total devolution or
decentralization of power.

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:18.480
Second thing is, unless there is
a spiritual foundation on which

00:53:18.480 --> 00:53:21.180
these people unite,
it won't work.

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:22.670
[INAUDIBLE]

00:53:22.670 --> 00:53:24.740
Again, demand
somebody from the top

00:53:24.740 --> 00:53:27.330
to send the army or the police
to say settle our dispute.

00:53:27.330 --> 00:53:27.945
This building.

00:53:27.945 --> 00:53:34.240
So second thing is a
spiritual awakening.

00:53:34.240 --> 00:53:39.535
Third thing is, while you
have that critical mass

00:53:39.535 --> 00:53:45.200
of spiritual consciousness,
keeping the people together,

00:53:45.200 --> 00:53:52.820
you need the most modern
communication technology

00:53:52.820 --> 00:53:58.340
going to every village, every
community, in the planet.

00:53:58.340 --> 00:54:02.650
To prepare for this we have
a section called fusion,

00:54:02.650 --> 00:54:06.330
because we really don't know
how to handle IT and all that.

00:54:06.330 --> 00:54:08.980
What I said what they were
doing me a good thing.

00:54:08.980 --> 00:54:11.640
We can reach more and more
and more and more people.

00:54:11.640 --> 00:54:13.720
And knowledge.

00:54:13.720 --> 00:54:20.530
So start training people in
this so at least a couple

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:24.120
of people in our villages
are competent to handle

00:54:24.120 --> 00:54:27.670
computers, the
internet, like that.

00:54:27.670 --> 00:54:32.450
Now that, we need a
lot of help from you.

00:54:32.450 --> 00:54:39.490
That is, if you can get
our 15,000 village network,

00:54:39.490 --> 00:54:44.915
which is now experimenting with
total decentralized banking.

00:54:47.610 --> 00:54:52.640
There are so many areas we
need help in technology.

00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:54.500
We are a very poor organization.

00:54:54.500 --> 00:54:57.000
We don't have a tax.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:01.990
For his donation he
gave some time ago,

00:55:01.990 --> 00:55:05.130
they did lot of work
including a good publication.

00:55:05.130 --> 00:55:08.410
I don't agree with the
theme of the publication.

00:55:08.410 --> 00:55:11.340
It happened to be
about a person.

00:55:11.340 --> 00:55:13.330
That is myself,
which I don't like.

00:55:17.710 --> 00:55:19.780
So many have helped
us in different ways.

00:55:19.780 --> 00:55:28.080
Now he is giving us first class,
western, scientific knowledge

00:55:28.080 --> 00:55:32.710
also combined with
eastern spirituality

00:55:32.710 --> 00:55:36.100
without spending a
cent on our part.

00:55:36.100 --> 00:55:40.380
So that way those who
have knowledge, money,

00:55:40.380 --> 00:55:43.390
and other expertise
should share it with us,

00:55:43.390 --> 00:55:45.170
we will share with you.

00:55:45.170 --> 00:55:51.900
We also have a lot of expertise
derived from ancient living

00:55:51.900 --> 00:55:55.630
culture normal in our village.

00:55:55.630 --> 00:55:57.001
SPEAKER: One minute.

00:55:57.001 --> 00:55:58.370
Any last words from you?

00:55:58.370 --> 00:56:00.370
DR. WALTER LINK: Yes.

00:56:00.370 --> 00:56:03.520
So I think you
spoke about courage.

00:56:03.520 --> 00:56:08.010
I think one of the most
important things that everybody

00:56:08.010 --> 00:56:11.540
could do is to have the
courage to really listen

00:56:11.540 --> 00:56:13.540
to their deepest inspiration.

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:17.100
I think we are very
discouraged in doing that.

00:56:17.100 --> 00:56:23.560
And then to really look at
every institution of our society

00:56:23.560 --> 00:56:28.630
and really look and see like how
can that really fully represent

00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:32.850
our humanity and the
sustainability that we want,

00:56:32.850 --> 00:56:37.180
and what can we
learn from Sarvodava?

00:56:37.180 --> 00:56:44.450
We are working, for example,
on a big movement outreach

00:56:44.450 --> 00:56:48.830
to reinvent democracy
which, also in this country

00:56:48.830 --> 00:56:51.465
and in many countries around
the world, as we know,

00:56:51.465 --> 00:56:57.870
get stale and formal
and loses the alive,

00:56:57.870 --> 00:57:01.560
dialogic, interchange where
we really get together

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:05.600
to co-create the
understanding of how

00:57:05.600 --> 00:57:07.500
we want to live together.

00:57:07.500 --> 00:57:09.800
So I think that's a
very interesting project

00:57:09.800 --> 00:57:11.060
that we could talk more about.

00:57:11.060 --> 00:57:15.340
Secondly, fact is
that businesses

00:57:15.340 --> 00:57:21.420
now impact society in
such a massive way,

00:57:21.420 --> 00:57:28.220
that we really need to think
about how to create companies

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:30.870
that really represent
this deepest inspiration,

00:57:30.870 --> 00:57:32.730
and so what we're
doing, for example, is

00:57:32.730 --> 00:57:37.600
we took a non profitable
nonprofit that

00:57:37.600 --> 00:57:43.220
was doing microfinance and
gave very good social service,

00:57:43.220 --> 00:57:47.820
but wasn't really a model
for reinventing the economy

00:57:47.820 --> 00:57:51.950
because it was just another
nice social institution.

00:57:51.950 --> 00:57:55.140
We are transforming that into
a fully regulated bank that

00:57:55.140 --> 00:57:58.800
presently is growing
at 100% every year

00:57:58.800 --> 00:58:03.960
and that requires really a
very big cultural change also

00:58:03.960 --> 00:58:10.460
in the organization where
people that we're used to just--

00:58:10.460 --> 00:58:16.320
be good, also had to integrate
being good as being really

00:58:16.320 --> 00:58:20.030
effective, and I think
this is also what we need.

00:58:20.030 --> 00:58:23.800
There is a good
challenge in business

00:58:23.800 --> 00:58:26.970
to integrate really
this deep humanity

00:58:26.970 --> 00:58:29.030
with doing it in
a way that works.

00:58:29.030 --> 00:58:32.730
And I think, for example,
when we look at innovation.

00:58:32.730 --> 00:58:36.910
Innovation isn't just doing
something new and different.

00:58:36.910 --> 00:58:40.430
It's doing something that really
serves the world, only then

00:58:40.430 --> 00:58:43.820
does it really deserve
the word innovation.

00:58:43.820 --> 00:58:46.680
And all of that will
only happen [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:46.680 --> 00:58:49.570
aspect that I think
we can learn here.

00:58:49.570 --> 00:58:56.110
Find a way for ourselves, how
we really develop our potential.

00:58:56.110 --> 00:59:00.140
Because it's not some kind
of theory, this potential,

